"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-07-28-uks-austerity-olympics-21294135\", \"entities\": [{\"sentence\": \"WhileFrancemay have dubbed their games the 'Popular Olympics', the competition has not always enjoyedParis' opulence.\", \"from\": 0, \"to\": 117, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Britain's own celebrations in 1948 were called the 'Austerity Olympics' and the games did not enjoy the scents of freshly baked croissants.\", \"from\": 119, \"to\": 258, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 119, \"end\": 126, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_Kingdom\", \"score\": 0.9911057118619618, \"rank\": 0.008884858096725278, \"text\": \"Britain\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_Kingdom\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_Kingdom\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"But as its combatants marked the end ofWorld War Twothe fires of compatriotism never burnt so bright.\", \"from\": 260, \"to\": 361, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"An 85,000-strong crowd arrived to watch the opening ceremony atWembleyPark, and global unity finally seemed to be a thing of the present - not just a hopeful wish.\", \"from\": 363, \"to\": 526, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"'The hour has struck, a visionary dream has today become a glorious reality,' Lord Burghley, opening the ceremony, said  'At the end of the worldwide struggle in 1945\\u2026 there is warm flame of hope for a better understanding in the world which has burned so low.'\", \"from\": 528, \"to\": 789, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 606, \"end\": 619, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/William_Cecil,_1st_Baron_Burghley\", \"score\": 0.9908206790853803, \"rank\": 0.008643451075177545, \"text\": \"Lord Burghley\", \"types\": [\"Q82955\", \"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/William_Cecil,_1st_Baron_Burghley\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/William_Cecil,_1st_Baron_Burghley\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In true London fashion, 2,500 pigeons were set free and King George VI declared the 'Austerity Games' to be open after a 12 year hiatus.\", \"from\": 791, \"to\": 927, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 799, \"end\": 805, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/London\", \"score\": 0.9999999705287341, \"rank\": 2.641364006447475e-08, \"text\": \"London\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/London\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/London\"}, {\"begin\": 847, \"end\": 861, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/George_VI\", \"score\": 0.9999998923103761, \"rank\": 1.0302909932986751e-07, \"text\": \"King George VI\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/George_VI\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/George_VI\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The financial and emotional cost of World War Two meant nearly every country was on its knees - but it was decided the prestigious event should return, with the UK asked to host.\", \"from\": 929, \"to\": 1107, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1090, \"end\": 1092, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_Kingdom\", \"score\": 0.9999998629373389, \"rank\": 1.0224560249430554e-07, \"text\": \"UK\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_Kingdom\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_Kingdom\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Unlike the flashy and successful London games in 2012, no new venues could possibly built just three years after the peace treaties were signed.\", \"from\": 1109, \"to\": 1253, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1142, \"end\": 1148, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/London\", \"score\": 0.9999999705287341, \"rank\": 2.641364006447475e-08, \"text\": \"London\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/London\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/London\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Athletes had to stay in sub par accommodation as London only just began rebuilding the thousands of bombed out buildings.\", \"from\": 1255, \"to\": 1376, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1304, \"end\": 1310, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/London\", \"score\": 0.9999999705287341, \"rank\": 2.641364006447475e-08, \"text\": \"London\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/London\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/London\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"To get the latest news from the capital, visit Metro'sLondon news hub.\", \"from\": 1378, \"to\": 1448, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1439, \"end\": 1447, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/News_Hub\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"news hub\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/News_Hub\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/News_Hub\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"British participants even hard to provide their own shorts and towels, with bed linen being provided half-heartedly.\", \"from\": 1450, \"to\": 1566, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1450, \"end\": 1457, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_Kingdom\", \"score\": 0.9974062113583357, \"rank\": 0.0023110257625614454, \"text\": \"British\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_Kingdom\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_Kingdom\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Team GB athlete Jack Braughton did his morning shift on a construction site before taking the tub to race in the 5,000 metre heats.\", \"from\": 1568, \"to\": 1699, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1584, \"end\": 1598, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jack_Braughton\", \"score\": 0.9999556832601572, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Jack Braughton\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jack_Braughton\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jack_Braughton\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Yet, a record 59 nations took part, with only a few countries - namely Germany, Japan and the Soviet Union - being banned or refusing to take part.\", \"from\": 1701, \"to\": 1848, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1772, \"end\": 1779, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nazi_Germany\", \"score\": 0.8287368024570894, \"rank\": 0.12187252956920239, \"text\": \"Germany\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nazi_Germany\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nazi_Germany\"}, {\"begin\": 1781, \"end\": 1786, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Empire_of_Japan\", \"score\": 0.6836255944255456, \"rank\": 0.46278053216671466, \"text\": \"Japan\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Empire_of_Japan\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Empire_of_Japan\"}, {\"begin\": 1802, \"end\": 1807, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_States\", \"score\": 0.9999998448070193, \"rank\": 1.2150269726970814e-07, \"text\": \"Union\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_States\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_States\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"No one tried to hide the games were held on a shoe string budget, but as expectations were already low, nations celebrated a feeling of being 'back to normal'.\", \"from\": 1850, \"to\": 2009, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"In total, 4,104 athletes took part across 19 different sports - an astounding number considering how many lost their lives over the war.\", \"from\": 2011, \"to\": 2147, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Highlights included Dutch sprinter and mother-of-two Fanny Blankers-Koen, aka the Flying Housewife, winning four gold medals in athletics.\", \"from\": 2149, \"to\": 2287, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2169, \"end\": 2174, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dutch_language\", \"score\": 0.672105059952145, \"rank\": 0.4532140151196018, \"text\": \"Dutch\", \"types\": [\"Q315\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dutch_language\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dutch_language\"}, {\"begin\": 2202, \"end\": 2207, \"title\": \"http://d